<Time>1596665907047<//Time><resp>{'time': 1596729725227, 'text': 'Good Morning John, I dont show you in my database as a client under the name of John Jacob but in reply to your assertion that we are not committed to our clients is totally untrue. Trial is the worst option 90% of the time in a workers compensation case since the future medical stays open at the end of the trial and the client only receives small biweekly payments till the amount of the award is paid in full.  The issue of the value of the injury itself is rather cut and dry based upon the doctors reporting of the disability involved and your attorney and the courts use the same rating system making trial on that issue unnecessary. Generally the only cases that go to trial is where the Employer has challenged the truthfulness of the alleged injury or the doctors assessment of apportionment to non-industrial factors.\nAs you must realize the attorney gets paid based upon the gross settlement and so it stands to reason he is not about to leave any money on the table so he and the client win.\nNo case is ever settled without the clients approval, this is not a back room deal done in the dark behind anyone\'s back. First of all no matter who you hire attorneys will only care about themselves they will tell you only what you want to hear you know the old saying the bloodsucking attorney.so you just have to pick lesser of the two evils. My experience with peter and his office started out well but than I started doing a lot of the foot work and dealing with bad doctors, than this office started making big mistakes I was actually cut off workers comp because they only pay for 104 weeks so I got on disibilty when the 3rd party attorney took it upon himself to cancel my disibilty without a notice or letter or even notifying my attorney. I came to Peter's office to discuss this and everyone there told could and wouldn't ever happen so I insisted that they call them and turns out that they did go over our heads to do so and was getting shorted my disibilty because the other attorney said I was getting permanent disibilty which I was wasn't and I never got back pay for that like they promised. At the end I had to settle the job I had was too physically demanding for my back the settlement I received was nothing compared to what I was making not even a years salary, but they made it seem like it was a big deal and it was far from that trying to encourage me that he had all kinds of jobs and was skilled in various areas that I would be fine like I was suppose to be impressed with his accomplishments. After I signed my career away I spoke to his assistant maira I still had to get surgery on my thumb and I had mentioned this to her she told to pay for it out of my settlement or when or if get another job just tell them you hurt your thumb so they will pay for your surgery, I shook my head in disbelief and disgust on how shady these attorneys are the whole experience was very stressful I loss weight I lossed sleep and I almost lossed my marriage and lossed a great career with ups after 17 years of service just a few years from my pension. If I had to do it again I would not. So I hope this helps anyone out there with a similar injury and questions about getting litigated. Don't try to work something with your employer believe it or not there are a lot of people who are not out to sue and get money but unfortunately this is the route we had to take.< /review>

< Review>
I brought my car here via Geico after someone had hit my car. The adjuster I met gave me a rough idea of the repairs to be done and was creating a quote but failed to see the substrate/cracked paint on my front bumper. After I pointed it out to him he happily adjusted the quote to include the paintwork.

A 2‚Äù portion on the inside lip of my front bumper had been torn off by the incident. I was expecting a new front bumper, but was told they were going to attempt to plastic weld and Jerry-rig my car back together. I said nothing but was not happy at the repair.

An hour after I had left I received a call saying they could not fix the bumper and would replace it using a cheap aftermarket bumper. I accepted and told them to proceed. They painted the new piece, but never bothered doing a test fitting for it. They then realized that it didn‚Äôt fit and had to return it, purchase an OEM bumper cover and paint that.

Overall; this company does the right thing for their customers, but is inefficient in doing so.</Review>

Our recent experience with Collision Pros in Auburn, CA was truly an A+ from start to finish! Great customer consultation and service, and they completed the project on time and without issue.

My teen son was in a parking lot fender bender with our 2007 Honda white CRV. The car suffered paint scrapes and some minor knicks, along with a dented wheel fender. Brian VonTress the owner immediately provided us options to consider even before seeing the live damage. He made thoughtful recommendations based on our needs and budget. The work was done as promised in less than 3 days - ahead of schedule! And what came back was a car that looked almost new. Better than it looked even when we bought it used! Brian and Jason were awesome to work with - absolutely the best! Thanks you Brian and Jason for excellent experience.< /review>

Justin Pratt<//user_name>
< Review>
My first experience here was like anything else.  Ryan, the Barber I had, did a great job with my hair cut.  I like his personality, he was professional, down to earth and did a great job.  As for the business side of it, the aesthetics are pretty cool.  The business model seems pretty cool as well.  i may or may not do the membership.  The one reason for 4 stars instead of 5?  $75 for a hair cut.  I took advantage of the 50% off the first visit which helped.  The membership is appealing as you get "2 Units" per month to apply to services.  I understand each service is 1 unit.  This would make a hair cut $40 and any other service (mani, pedi, shave, etc.) also $40.  If you get groomed regularly, this is probably a good deal.  However, for the one off hair cut, I can't justify $75 for 20 minutes in the chair.  Hot towel, head massage, etc., I get that at other places charging 1/2 as much for a men's haircut.< /Review>

< Text>
I found dr Morley when my dog needed a check up and some shots. My pup was a pit so finding a dr where I didnt need to muzzle him was great! Dr Morley shared that he loved pits and they are some of his best patients. We were in and out very quickly, and he only charges us for the cost of coming in for a visit. I began using him for all 3 of my dogs. When I got one of my pits, he was used as a bait dog and found on the road. He wouldnt stand up, would cry every time he moved, had a skin condition... it was devastating. Dr Morley had him all fixed up within a few weeks of treatment. When my oldest got cancer, dr Morley told me to take her home, give her some meds for her pain but give her all the loving I could for a few days, then return to end her suffering. I really appreciated his kindness and again he did not cost an arm and a leg for these services. My other baby boy began having an issue and became VERY lethargic (which was SUPER out of the ordinary as he was usually very, very hyper and jumped up all over the place - he was only 5), wouldnt eat, wouldnt drink, would try pooping but not much would come out, and kept vomiting foamy bile. I had moved quite a ways away so I took him to 2 other vets who both gave him shots and meds. Nothing worked. After about a week and a half and $2,000 of trying to figure it out, I finally decided to make the drive back to dr Morley. He gave him one shot. My boy drank within 20 minutes, ate within a few hours, pooped that night and not once did he vomit again. I am positive dr Morley saved him from very possible death as it had been 2 weeks that he refused to eat, drink or poop and just kept vomiting. I live very far away now and told my husband I dont want to get another dog unless we move closer to dr Morley so I have a trusted vet. Thank you dr morley!!! <time>1613292636513<//time>< text>
Between the relatively 'sceneic' exercise trail around the exterior of park; spacious fields for soccer or baseball activities; solo tennis court.....and executive 3-part playground for the wee lil lads- I'd say this park has a great blend of everything for every type of person wanting to enjoy the urban outdoors.
The bathrooms are done by [www . publicrestroomcompany . com] ...so you know that the facilities are gonna be reliably in order. Lol

HOWEVER~
This park gets only a 4/5 star rating from me because of the dyslexic design of the basketball 'court' .... The court is shaped like a boomerang and requires you to shoot free throws 2.5 feet's to the left in order to be straight-on with the hoop. Any real hooper dribbling around on this court would feel awkward. Oh, and one of the rims is so loosey goosey (rattles every non-swish shot)...you better hope u score the 1 good hoop or you've just flushed your practice sesh. Attached are pics of the botched bball court ..

PS contrary to popular belief, the morning physical trainer guy isn't that bad. Just tell him that he's in the way. He'll move.<//text>

<user_name>Jaime Williams</user_name>< Text>
One of my favorite gambling spots.  Some of their slots are rip offs but some pretty much hit all the time.  I am digging Wheel of Fortune currently.  They have very reasonably priced food they will bring right to you at the slots.  Chicken strips and fries for instance or milk shakes and hamburgers.  Simple but yummy.  Restrooms are always clean and there's always security 24/7 to help with any concerns.  I left my phone in the ladies once, got all the way home ( about an hour) before i realized it, called them, and wow! They had it.  I had to prove it was mine by calling it, then unlocking it, and finally my id so they are on it. There is also a Bingo hall there and a handful of card tables.  I definitely recommend this Indian owned casino   for great evening of entertainment. And since reopening after covid masks are required as is a temperature check. And of social distancing.  There is plexi glass between slot machines.</Text>

<text>Chicken Ranch is a funny name for a small, out of the way casino. The road leading to the casino is pretty tore up & a bit misleading. Just as you think something is wrong or maybe it's the wrong road, there it is! The casino is under construction as they are building a brand new bingo hall. They have moved the parking lot to across the street which, as of now is gravel. After finding your way in (main entrance is gated off) Chicken Ranch offers a variety of slots but no tables. It is a bit smokey & offers no non-smoking areas, except the bingo hall. There is a restaurant inside that offers very good food. It's a small cafe style, to sit g eat or they have finger foods available as well. They seem to be short staffed on waitresses often so don't count on one coming to offer a drink. Also only one ticket machine in the whole place or you can change a ticket at the cash cage where 2 ladies sit. If the place is packed which it usually is, plan on waiting in a line. Other than not having enough slots to accommodate all the players who visit it's great. Benches are available to those who just like to sit, free wifi, self serve coffee bar & free parking lot shuttle service are a few amenities offered here.<//text>< Pictures>

< name>
Lindsey Amanda</name>
< date>
1541816699978< /date>
<Rate>4< /Rate>< Text>
Chicken Ranch is a funny name for a small, out of the way casino. The road leading to the casino is pretty tore up & a bit misleading. Just as you think something is wrong or maybe it's the wrong road, there it is! The casino is under construction as they are building a brand new bingo hall. They have moved the parking lot to across the street which, as of now is gravel. After finding your way in (main entrance is gated off) Chicken Ranch offers a variety of slots but no tables. It is a bit smokey & offers no non-smoking areas, except the bingo hall. There is a restaurant inside that offers very good food. It's a small cafe style, to sit g eat or they have finger foods available as well. They seem to be short staffed on waitresses often so don't count on one coming to offer a drink. Also only one ticket machine in the whole place or you can change a ticket at the cash cage where 2 ladies sit. If the place is packed which it usually is, plan on waiting in a line. Other than not having enough slots to accommodate all the players who visit it's great. Benches are available to those who just like to sit, free wifi, self serve coffee bar & free parking lot shuttle service are a few amenities offered here.</Text>

The casino, however, is small and not a comfortable environment to gamble in.  Between tight/cramped  spaces, constantly full of smoke and its clientele I usually don't like to spend much time in playing there.  The machines appear to be set amongst the lowest "payout" in comparison to similar casinos. The players card is even lacking any real incentive to return with very little "free play". They lack updated games that are popular.  The casino also has an extremely short supply of the more desired machines that lead to customers waiting for available machines and players often saving them as they leave for extended periods of time, often times not returning. The casino also allows non-playing customers tie up popular machines by to sitting and visiting with others as waiting customers look on and wait. Because of it's location the casino has an issue with subjects obviously under the influence of narcotics and often ask for money from other customers.
